04778nmm a2200601Ia 9781501700811DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979581316  a97815017008117 a10.7591/97815017008112doi  a(DE-B1597)478574  a(OCoLC)927073956  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY0481pa333.7qDE-1011 aSullivan, Timothy J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAir Pollutant Deposition and Its Effects on Natural Resources in New York State /cTimothy J. Sullivan. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2015] 4cÂ©2015  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b12-page color map insert, 3 black-and-white maps, 19 charts  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEcosystem effects from air pollution in the Adirondacks, Catskills, and elsewhere in New York have been substantial. Efforts to characterize and quantify these impacts, and to examine more recent recovery, have focused largely on surface waters, soils, and forests. Lakes, streams, and soils have acidified. Estuaries have become more eutrophic. Nutrient cycles have been disrupted. Mercury has bioaccumulated to toxic levels. Plant species composition has changed. Some surface waters show signs of partial chemical recovery in response to emissions control programs, but available data suggest that soil chemistry may continue to deteriorate under expected future emissions and deposition. Resource managers, policymakers, and scientists now need to know the extent to which current and projected future emissions reductions will lead to ecosystem recovery.In this book, Timothy J. Sullivan provides a comprehensive synthesis of past, current, and potential future conditions regarding atmospheric sulfur, nitrogen oxides, ammonium, and mercury deposition; surface water chemistry; soil chemistry; forests; and aquatic biota in New York, providing much needed information to help set emissions reduction goals, evaluate incremental improvements, conduct cost/benefit analyses, and prioritize research needs. He draws upon a wealth of research conducted over the past thirty years that has categorized, quantified, and advanced understanding of ecosystem processes related to atmospheric deposition of strong acids, nutrients, and mercury and associated ecosystem effects. An important component of this volume is the new interest in the management and mitigation of ecosystem damage from air pollution stress, which builds on the "critical loads" approach pioneered in Europe and now gaining interest in the United States. This book will inform scientists, resource managers, and policy analysts regarding the state of scientific knowledge on these complex topics and their policy relevance and will help to guide public policy assessment work in New York, the Northeast, and nationally.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aAirxPollutionxEnvironmental aspectszNew York (State). 0aAtmospheric depositionzNew York (State). 0aEnvironmental degradationzNew York (State). 0aNatural resourcesxEnvironmental aspectszNew York (State). 4aEnvironmental History. 4aGeneral Science. 4aNature Guides & Natural History.  apollution, air pollutants, air pollution stress, climate change, natural resources, New York, ecosystem, emissions control, emissions reduction, ecosystem recovery, environmental health, science of environmental response, policymaking.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170081140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501700811423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501700811/origina